11 (4) Before issuing an order that interprets a statute in this chapter that is administered by a
12 governing body, the court shall invite any governing body who administers the statute to participate as an
13 amicus curiae and file a brief in the case. The court shall wait a sufficient time after issuing the invitation to
14 allow an interested governing body to file an amicus brief with the court. The court shall allow a governing body,
15 a group of governing bodies, or an association whose membership is composed of governing bodies to file an
16 amicus brief under this subsection.
17 (5) A nonparty who files a brief as an amicus curiae under subsection (4) may intervene in the
18 case after an order has been issued interpreting a statute in this chapter and may seek a stay of that order
19 pending appeal. The court shall grant the stay until the issue is finally resolved on appeal.
20 (4)(6) For the purposes of this section, "aggrieved" means a person who can demonstrate a specific
21 personal and legal interest, as distinguished from a general interest, who has been or is likely to be specially
22 and injuriously affected by the decision."
23
24 Section 2. Section 76-25-503, MCA, is amended to read:
25 "76-25-503. Appeals -- amicus brief -- intervention. (1) Appeals of any final decisions made
26 pursuant to this chapter must be made in accordance with this section.
27 (2) For a challenge to the adoption of or amendment to a land use plan, zoning regulation, zoning
28 map, or subdivision regulation, a petition setting forth the basis for the challenge must be presented to the
